003E is a thin membrane of tissue that protrudes into the oesophageal lumen, representing a true structural obstruction (Image). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse oesophageal spasm\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Enutcracker oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E are motility disorders characterised by uncoordinated contractions of the oesophagus.  \u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily a motility disorder characterised by failure of lower oesophageal sphincter relaxation and loss of peristalsis. \u003Cstrong\u003EOesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition that can cause dysphagia through pain and swelling but is not primarily a structural obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysphagia can be classified into structural/obstructive causes and neuromuscular/motility disorders.","Achalasia is a structural disorder characterized by failure of lower oesophageal sphincter relaxation and loss of peristalsis.","Diffuse oesophageal spasm and nutcracker oesophagus are motility disorders."],"references":["Panebianco M, Marchese-Ragona R, Masiero S, Restivo DA. Dysphagia in neurological diseases: a literature review. Neurol Sci. 2020 Nov;41(11):3067-3073. doi: 10.1007/s10072-020-04495-2. Epub 2020 Jun 7. PMID: 32506360; PMCID: PMC7567719.","Wilkinson JM, Codipilly DC, Wilfahrt RP. Dysphagia: Evaluation and Collaborative Management. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Jan 15;103(2):97-106. PMID: 33448766.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50011"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15118"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21